description: Believes in gradual progress and institutional reform; sees America as imperfect but improving. Votes Democratic with confidence rather than fear.
examples: Joe Biden, Tim Walz, Obama coalition optimists

description: Morning-in-America optimism; believes in American dynamism and that conservative policies will restore prosperity. Forward-looking rather than defensive.
examples: Reagan heirs, Chamber of Commerce optimists, Nikki Haley

description: Defends traditional culture and hierarchy against perceived threats; cultural identity is central to politics.
Maximum cultural defense posture; pessimistic about reversing decline but committed to holding the line.
Holds no strong political views; content with status quo and avoids political engagement. Politics is irrelevant distraction. 'I just want to grill.'
examples: Michael Jordan (1990s), Derek Jeter, Tim Duncan

description: Believes progress lifts everyone; combines social liberalism with genuine optimism about human potential and positive-sum politics.
Focuses on bread-and-butter issues but believes smart economic policy can grow the pie for everyone. Solutions-oriented, less combative than populist wing.
examples: Jason Furman types, pragmatic union leaders, suburban economic Democrats

description: Works through established institutions to achieve progressive goals; believes in reform within the system.
examples: Hillary Clinton, Nancy Pelosi, Chuck Schumer

description: Sees humanity as interconnected; prioritizes international cooperation and universal human rights over national boundaries.
examples: Samantha Power, Angelina Jolie, George Clooney

description: Combines free-market economics with traditional values and strong national identity; Reaganite fusion conservative.
examples: Ted Cruz, Ron DeSantis, Marco Rubio

description: Views politics through lens of class struggle; corporations and billionaires are the enemy. Economic redistribution is the terminal goal.
Economic freedom is the primary value; government intervention in markets is the main concern. Culture is secondary.
examples: Steve Forbes, Larry Kudlow, Art Laffer

description: Represents the mathematical center of American opinion; no strong ideological commitments on any dimension.
Religious faith and scripture are the foundation of political knowledge; family and church structure are paramount.
"Follow the data" as methodology for achieving progressive ends. Epistemology is instrumental but load-bearing.
Supports markets based on empirical evidence of efficiency; economics-first worldview grounded in data.
examples: Larry Summers, Greg Mankiw, Tyler Cowen

description: Committed ideological conservative active in the movement; fuses economics, culture, and nationalism with combative style.
Believes growth can benefit everyone; seeks win-win solutions across partisan lines. Positive-sum worldview is central.
Faith rooted in local community and inherited tradition; the church as anchor against a changing world. Heritage-preserving, locally focused religious voter.
examples: Traditional parish leaders, Southern Baptist community, Orthodox congregations

description: Regional/cultural identity drives politics; "common sense" epistemology; suspicious of outsiders and elites.
Lived experience and testimony are epistemically central; ethno-racial identity drives political positions.
Derives political positions from first principles and logical deduction; believes in human reason and markets.
Politics is about vision and hope; the aesthetic of uplift and inspiration IS the politics.
Moral witness IS the politics; speaking truth to power regardless of effectiveness.
Politics is competition; pro-market but sees economy as zero-sum race.
Believes in human perfectibility through reason; transformative potential of collective action.
Pro-business moderate who believes entrepreneurship solves social problems; not strongly partisan.
examples: Michael Bloomberg, Mark Cuban, Howard Schultz

description: Holds conservative views but avoids political engagement; votes but doesn't advocate.
Combines progressive economics with cosmopolitan internationalism; believes in global cooperation.
Sees politics as existential warfare between in-group and threatening out-groups.
examples: Marjorie Taylor Greene, Steve Bannon, Matt Gaetz

description: Progressive on economics, rooted in local community and often faith tradition.
Strongly pro-business but primarily motivated by partisan team loyalty.
Believes redistribution can happen through growth, not conflict; abundance mentality.
Takes positions from both parties; resists ideological conformity and tribal pressure. Actually has no partisan lean; evaluates each election independently.
examples: Bill Maher, Joe Rogan (2015â€“2020), Angus King

description: Culturally liberal with genuine optimism about human nature and social progress.
The quality of democratic conversation IS the value; civility matters intrinsically.
Globally-oriented moderate who values international institutions and cultural openness. Non-partisan with universalist values; heterodox on most issues.
examples: Fareed Zakaria, Thomas Friedman, Steven Pinker

description: Strong attachment to local community and civic institutions but centrist on economics/culture.
Believes most political problems have solutions that benefit everyone; actively seeks compromise.
examples: Larry Hogan, Charlie Baker, Jon Huntsman

description: Maximum commitment to traditional values, hierarchy, and in-group boundaries; no compromise.
Skeptical of national boundaries and in-group preferences; believes in universal humanity.
Actively seeks compromise across partisan divides; frustrated by tribalism on both sides.
Socially liberal, economically market-friendly; believes markets and social progress are compatible.
examples: Matt Yglesias, Noah Smith, Elon Musk (2012â€“2020)

description: Evaluates policies on merits rather than party affiliation; frustrated with partisan tribalism.
examples: Mitt Romney (2019â€“), Liz Cheney (2021â€“), Kyrsten Sinema (2020â€“)

description: Focuses on practical problem-solving rather than ideological purity.
Combines aggressive capitalism with authoritarian cultural conservatism; outcomes justify means.
Believes in free markets and free trade across borders; economically libertarian globalist.
Left-leaning but epistemology is load-bearing; follows evidence to progressive conclusions.
Economically left, culturally conservative working-class; wants redistribution but distrusts cultural outsiders. The 'Obama-Trump' crossover type.
examples: Robert Casey Sr. â€ , Huey Long â€ , Father Coughlin â€

description: Socially liberal, economically libertarian, globally oriented; dislikes both parties equally.
Centrist on economics but cautious about rapid cultural change.
examples: Suburban moderates uneasy with cultural progressivism

description: Believes fundamental transformation requires confrontation with entrenched power.
Values social order, hierarchy, and strong community bonds.
Progressive values rooted in strong community or faith tradition.
Supports social democratic policies but dislikes Democratic Party establishment.
Focuses on being a good community member; believes in local cooperation and mutual aid.
Free markets plus social liberalism; globalist, pro-immigration, optimistic about growth.
Social market economy; markets need strong rules and institutions to function fairly.
Center-right with religious moral framework; supports welfare state within traditional values.
Worker ownership combined with market mechanisms; anti-capitalist but not anti-market.
Land value tax as primary policy; believes unearned land rents are the source of inequality.
Active citizenship and civic virtue are essential; constitutional process is sacred. Freedom through participation; popular sovereignty within constitutional bounds.
examples: Hannah Arendt tradition, Federalist Society members, Larry Kramer

description: Strong communities over individual rights; moderate on economics and culture.
Triangulation between left and right; market-friendly progressivism. Pro-business, socially liberal, pragmatic.
Fiscally conservative, socially moderate; old-school northeastern Republican.
Radical Catholic social teaching; pacifist, pro-poor, anti-state.
Widespread property ownership; against both big business and big government.
Rural-focused; suspicious of banks, corporations, and urban elites.
Local self-governance is paramount; skeptical of all distant authority.
Market anarchism; free markets without capitalism, mutual credit.
Worker control through trade guilds or councils; decentralized socialism with workplace democracy.
Economic leftism combined with cultural conservatism; working-class traditionalist.
Nation-state as primary unit; cultural preservation, skeptical of globalism.
National identity based on civic values, not ethnicity; patriotic liberal.
Minimal state; only police, courts, military. Night-watchman state.
Abolish state and capitalism; mutual aid and gift economy.
Revolutionary trade unionism; workers control through direct action.
Civilization is the problem; return to pre-industrial or pre-agricultural life.
Technology will transcend human limitations; embrace enhancement.
Expert rule; policy should be determined by technical knowledge.
Reward talent and effort; inequality is acceptable if earned.
Democracy needs competent leadership; not all opinions equal on technical matters.
Authoritarian environmentalism; population control, deep ecology with force.
Synthesis of far-left economics and far-right nationalism.

Holds traditional values but applies them universally to all humans, not just their own tribe. Believes in timeless moral truths that transcend cultural and national boundaries. May be religious universalist or natural law adherent.
examples: Catholic social teaching adherents, natural law philosophers, some religious humanitarians, cosmopolitan conservatives

description: Beyond traditional anarchism; individualist, anti-organizational.
Neoreaction; democracy is a failed experiment, return to traditional authority.
Synthesize best ideas from all sides; reject tribal politics.
Politics itself is the problem; withdrawal, prefigurative alternatives.
Tech platform oligarchy as new feudalism; accepts this as inevitable.
Automation will eliminate scarcity; prepare for abundance.
examples: Fully automated luxury space communism memes

description: FALC; technology enables communist utopia without sacrifice.
Too focused on economic survival to engage in politics; sees politics as zero-sum but irrelevant to daily life.
examples: Working multiple jobs; politics is a luxury

description: Progressive values but not politically engaged; lives values privately.
examples: Socially liberal professionals who avoid politics

description: Politics is primarily social; votes how their community votes.
Participates through proper channels; believes in following rules and procedures.
Highly engaged online but doesn't participate offline; politics as entertainment.
examples: Twitter power users who never vote

description: Silently disagrees with both parties; keeps head down and disengages.
Constitutional process is sacred; outcomes are legitimate only if process is. Will oppose "their side" on procedural grounds.
examples: Ron Paul (civil liberties), some ACLU types

description: Institutionalist who cares about norms above outcomes; "how we do things" defines political identity.
examples: Adam Kinzinger, David French, Liz Cheney (J6 focus)

description: Markets + evidence + proper process; technocratic governance as ideal. Depoliticization is the goal.
First-principles reasoning + technical competence; believes rational analysis should drive policy.
Protest-oriented activist; believes in direct action and movement politics; prophetic style in the streets.
examples: DeRay Mckesson, John Lewis â€ , Dolores Huerta

description: Tradition is *how we know*, not just *what we prefer*; reason is limited; accumulated wisdom trumps abstract theory.
Loves analyzing politics but never participates; pundit mindset without action.
HOW we engage is the core political issue; incivility and polarization are the primary problems.
Progressive goals, evidence-based methods, principled about process; reform must be both effective and sound.
Highly engaged in politics but refuses partisan identity; advocates for issues rather than parties. Believes both parties are captured by special interests.
examples: Ralph Nader, some civic reform advocates, League of Women Voters activists

description: Votes based on specific issues rather than party loyalty; highly engaged but switches parties based on candidates and issues.
Believes participation itself is the highest political value; votes, volunteers, attends meetings regardless of party. Process-focused independent.
Extremely combative online but rarely participates offline. Politics as spectator sport and identity performance. High engagement online, zero offline.
examples: Twitter/Reddit political posters who never vote, reply guys

description: Loves political arguments and debate but sees voting as pointless. High conflict engagement, low civic participation.
examples: Political podcast addicts who don't vote, debate club alumni

description: Would prefer to be independent but feels forced to choose sides by polarization. High engagement, uncomfortable with party identity.
examples: 'I'm not a Democrat, I just always vote for them', Never-Trumpers

description: Fiscally centrist but socially progressive; open to cultural change while pragmatic on economics. Common among educated suburbanites.
examples: Suburban moderates who vote on social issues, 'socially liberal, fiscally moderate' types

description: Fiscally centrist but culturally traditional; values stability and tradition while pragmatic on economics. Common in rural and religious communities.
examples: Rural moderates, church-going centrists uncomfortable with both parties

description: Progressive economics framed through American civic identity; believes in shared national purpose, worker solidarity, and cross-partisan coalition building. Patriotic framing of progressive goals. Visionary rather than technocratic.
examples: Ro Khanna, Tim Ryan (economic focus), some Bernie coalition members

description: Social democratic economics combined with civic nationalism. Believes in rebuilding American identity around civic participation, shared democratic values, and economic solidarity. Policy-focused rather than populist; sees national cohesion through inclusive institutions.
examples: Union Democrats, civic renewal advocates, some New Deal coalition inheritors

description: Worried about democratic backsliding, climate crisis, or authoritarian threats; votes with urgency and alarm. Sees elections as existential battles.
Feels traditional America is under siege from cultural and demographic change; votes defensively to preserve what remains of the country they knew.
examples: Laura Ingraham listeners, cultural anxiety voters

description: Sees economics as zero-sum struggle between workers and the powerful; combative 'fighting for working families' framing. Economic combat, not wonkery.
examples: Sherrod Brown supporters, union Democrats, populist left

description: Faith calls them to universal justiceâ€”welcoming the stranger, caring for the poor, healing the world. Cosmopolitan, interfaith-friendly, progressive religious tradition.
examples: William Barber, Jim Wallis, liberation theology Catholics, progressive evangelicals

description: "It's all rigged." Disengaged or purely expressive politics.
Institutions can be reformed to achieve transformative goals.
Works within institutions because that's what works; no illusions about transformation.
Markets plus progress can solve everything; techno-optimist.
Markets are the least bad option; no illusions about perfection.

Believes in human potential but distrusts institutions. Sees bureaucracies, corporations, and governments as corrupting forces that stifle human goodness. Prefers grassroots, community-based, and direct approaches over institutional channels.
examples: Some localists, mutual aid organizers, back-to-land movement, skeptical community activists

description: Traditional values are under permanent attack from hostile forces; defensive, embattled, sees betrayal everywhere.
examples: Culture war conservatives, Benedict Option types

description: Believes hard work leads to prosperity; optimistic about economic mobility and the American Dream.
Worried about economic security and falling behind; needs reassurance that the system hasn't forgotten them.
No coherent ideology; activated by zero-sum framing and anti-elite messaging. Votes AGAINST system, not FOR policy. First-time Trump voter archetype.
examples: 2016 Obamaâ†’Trump voters; non-voters activated by Trump

description: High threat sensitivity; responds to "things are getting worse" messaging. Swings based on which party seems more threatening. No coherent ideology.
examples: Anxious swing voters in Rust Belt
